         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">In <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2007"/><citedRange>№450</citedRange></bibl>, this line was read <hi>/// tno tpā<hi rend="underline">t</hi>[\], 1 [po] ///</hi>. Without making explicit why, <bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2009"/><citedRange>124</citedRange></bibl> prefers to read <hi>/// nto rwā <hi rend="underline">ta</hi>ṃ p· ///</hi>. Although one may disagree on some details, I can definitely not accept his reading <hi>rwā</hi>. My current reading <hi>(ci)ttotpāt po(sāt)</hi> sees here a Tocharianised form of Skt. <hi>cittotpādapoṣatha</hi> "Beichtfeier aufgrund des Fassens eines Vorsatzes, Entschlusses" (<bibl><title corresp="ref:swft1973"/></bibl> II: 253a).</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment"><hi>we-</hi>: probably <hi>we(ṣṣäṃ)</hi> "he says".</note></p>
         </div>
